State of Bitcoin Q3 2024

Sunny Shi

Oct 25, 2024   10 min read

Key Insights

  • BTCs price increased 5% QoQ to $66,083, experiencing pronounced two-sided volatility as price action remained choppy. Narrative drivers are largely macroeconomic.
  • Spot BTC ETFs impressed with a bounce-back quarter, contributing close to $5 billion in net inflows in Q3, up 73%. They now hold over 900,000 BTC, cumulatively.
  • Halved block rewards and rising hashrate ate into miner profitability. Miner revenues declined 30% QoQ.
  • Ordinals and runes activity continues to cascade. However, certain NFT collections and assets have found a way to remain relevant following the initial drawdown.
  • TVL on programmable Bitcoin layers increased 20% QoQ, while LRT TVL surged following the launch of Babylons first staking round. Core and Lombard are early winners in these respective categories.

Primer

Bitcoin (BTC) is the first distributed consensus-based, peer-to-peer payment settlement network. Bitcoin (BTC), the native asset of the Bitcoin blockchain, was the world's first digital currency without a central bank or administrator. Often referred to as digital gold, bitcoin has a predictable, stable monetary policy that operates autonomously, giving it the ideal store-of-value properties.

To secure its network, Bitcoin uses a Proof-of-Work (PoW) consensus mechanism to solve the double-spend problem. PoW requires participants (miners) to contribute computing power to solve arbitrary mathematical puzzles in order to add a new block to the blockchain. Bitcoin is awarded to the miner who solves the puzzle first, thus minting new bitcoins.

Bitcoin has historically been focused solely on enabling peer-to-peer payments and acting as a store of value, without any activity surrounding DeFi, NFTs, and other narratives enabled by programmability (i.e., expressive smart contracts and arbitrary computation). In the past year, recent developments have spurred a renaissance of utility and programmability for the network, largely thanks to innovations like Ordinal Theory, BitVM, Runes and Babylon. These innovations either leverage offchain indexing/computation or existing Bitcoin infrastructure and thus, do not require any changes be made to the underlying network. The aforementioned changes have sparked a frenzy of experimentation with onchain assets, modular layers and new avenues for BTC utility. In the midst of a potential paradigm shift, Bitcoins qualities and value proposition as a blockchain continues to remain fluid.

Key Metrics

Performance Analysis

Financial Overview

BTCs price was up 5% QoQ, ending Q3 around ~$66,000. Since setting an all-time-high in March, BTC has mostly been range-bound. The asset experienced a particularly volatile trading week in August during the unwind of the yen carry trade, where it fell from roughly $70,000 to under $50,000 within eight trading days. Volatility remained elevated throughout the quarter, with levered speculation resulting in numerous leverage flushes. Now that the halving and Fed rate cuts are in the rearview mirror, BTCs narratives have shifted towards the upcoming U.S. election, global liquidity, and institutional demand. Bitcoins market cap dominance remained robust, sitting at 53% at the end of the quarter, up from 50.6% in Q2.

ETF flows continue to be supportive, with April being the only month with net outflows. Spot Bitcoin ETFs contributed close to $5 billion in net inflows throughout Q3, up 73% QoQ. While Grayscales GBTC remains a net seller, September marked its lowest month for outflows at $328 million, and other issuers more than compensated for its impact. Notably, Blackrocks IBIT has been the most consequential driver of net inflows pouring in $3.7 billion in net inflows for Q3 and registering only three days of net outflows since inception.

At the end of the quarter, the ETFs assets under management (AUM) approached 1 million BTC, increasing by 9%. IBIT and GBTC remain the two largest holders of Bitcoin among the ETFs, holding 363,060 and 219,541 BTC, respectively. AUM growth has sustained despite muted price appreciation and high volatility, a positive sign of institutional demand. Early indicators show that BTC inflows have picked up further in October.

Supply

Bitcoins circulating supply increased by 0.21% to 19.76 million in Q3, its first full quarter since Aprils halving. Block rewards have dropped to 3.125 BTC, which has consequently reduced Bitcoins daily issuance.

Miner revenues declined 30%, driven by BTCs lower average price, muted transaction fees, and the impact of a full quarter of reduced block rewards. In Q3, Bitcoin spent approximately $28 million a day on security, with transaction fees dropping to just 2% of the security budget, down from 10% the quarter prior.

Network Overview

Bitcoins average monthly active addresses increased by 5%, while average monthly transactions rose by 11%. The uptick in activity could be attributed to several potential factors, including heightened price volatility, ETF spot purchases, election-driven speculation, and growing TVL in rollups and restaking (as discussed further below).

Hashrate represents the computational cost and resource demands faced by miners who secure the Bitcoin network. As hashrate increases, miner profitability decreases (assuming a constant BTC price). In Q3, Bitcoins average daily hashrate increased by 5%, reaching an all-time-high.

Reduced block rewards post-halving, along with increased competition, have eroded miner profitability. A notable emerging trend among established Bitcoin miners is the diversion of computational resources towards powering AI as an alternative use of infrastructure, particularly during periods of low profitability. As discussed in our previous State of Bitcoin report, hashrate has also become increasingly commoditized as interest in programmability grows.

Ecosystem Overview

Ordinals and Runes

Over the last two quarters, the number of inscriptions on the Bitcoin network has seen a drastic decline, marking a pronounced reversal from the mania that swept through 2023 and early 2024. Q3 was a continuation of this falling trend, with average daily inscriptions decreasing 34% down to ~26,000.

In conjunction, demand for ordinals has also sharply deteriorated, with NFT volumes on leading exchanges declining 81%. Magic Eden continues to host the majority of ordinals-related volume, ending the quarter with an 83% volume share.

Since the introduction of runes, Casey Rodarmors fungible Bitcoin token standard, their usage has largely displaced and surpassed that of the BRC-20 fungible token standard. Runes are often viewed as more economically viable considering BRC-20s UTXO inefficiencies and have replaced them to become the most widely transacted Bitcoin alternative token standard. This remained the case in Q3, although their transaction share declined against standard BTC transactions. BTCs average daily transaction share increased to 88% in Q3 from 70% in Q2, as activity within Bitcoin alts slowed.

Despite waning activity, interest for select assets have persisted. Ordinals collections like NodeMonkes and Bitcoin Puppets remain in the top 10 NFT collections by market capitalization, while runes like DOGGOTOTHEMOON and PUPSWORLDPEACE command nine-figure valuations and have recovered from their lows. For growth to resume, the user experience likely has to improve, as slow block times, limited programmability, and subpar liquidity on the Bitcoin network have created heavy sources of friction.

Sidechains and Staking

Interest in Bitcoin scaling solutions has heightened after clear demand emerged for alternative assets on the network. Similar to Ethereum rollups, Bitcoin layer-2s offload indexing or computation offchain. Currently, implementations are being explored incorporating multiple virtual machines (VMs), including the EVM and SVM.

In Q3, Bitcoin programmable layers continued to attract more TVL, with total TVL surging 20%, breaching $1.4 billion. Core was the largest gainer and overall contributor, growing its TVL 4.6x throughout the quarter, overtaking Bitlayer, Rootstock, and Merlin. It remains to be seen whether Bitcoin layers will prove to be a winners-takes-most market, as differentiation among the leading solutions has yet to emerge. Furthermore, the development pipeline remains crowded, with over 40 total layers announced to date.

A new development in the quarter was the ramp-up of Babylons offering. Babylon is Bitcoins first staking protocol built directly on the Bitcoin network, offering a unique approach to leveraging Bitcoin's immense economic security. The protocol enables Bitcoin holders to stake their BTC, providing security for other networks in exchange for staking rewards. This system resembles Ethereums EigenLayer, with the caveat being that Babylon aims to harness Bitcoins $1.2 trillion market cap, making it an even more attractive asset for shared security.

Babylon raised $18 million at the end of 2023 to develop a security and aggregation layer between Bitcoin and various Proof-of-Stake (PoS) networks. Babylon allows BTC to remain on Bitcoins mainnet while delegating its security to other chains. BTC holders can lock their assets in Babylon, choose the networks they wish to support and earn staking rewards without relinquishing control of their BTC.

A key feature of Babylon is its "Remote Staking," which ensures that BTC staking is done in a self-custodial manner, without relying on third parties like custodians. Babylons innovative use of Bitcoins scripting language enables staking, slashing, and other security functions, all while adhering to Bitcoins decentralized ethos.

Babylons first staking round for 1,000 BTC occurred in August, hitting its cap within six blocks. Liquid Restaking Tokens (LRTs), like Lombards LBTC, allow staked BTC to be restaked into Babylon and other restaking protocols, enabling native yield while maintaining liquidity and DeFi composability. In the quarter, LRT deposits rose 277x to $880 million in TVL, with Lombard and Solv attracting $397 million and $274 million, respectively.

Closing Summary

Bitcoin has experienced a volatile quarter, both in terms of BTC price action and onchain activity. ETF inflows have recovered after a down Q2, as Blackrock continues to drive net flows while Grayscale outflows soften. Macroeconomic events, such as the Yen carry trade unwind, September rate cuts, global instability, and speculation on the US election, have controlled the narrative following last quarters halving.

Although some of the onchain frenzy, particularly in inscriptions and runes, has waned, innovations like programmable layers and BTC restaking have flourished. The launch and swift conclusion of Babylons first staking round in August marked a significant moment, as native BTC staking was introduced at scale. As we move into Q4, Bitcoin continues to evolve its identity, both as an asset and a network.
